This project concerns some nonlinear partial differential equations (PDEs) that appear naturally in physics, economics, and engineering and that arise, for example, in the study of crystal growth, composite materials, combustion, game theory, and optimal control theory. The equations studied have deep connections with a host of other areas of mathematics, including the calculus of variations, differential games, dynamical systems, geometry, homogenization theory, and inverse problems. The main goal of the project is to discover new underlying principles and general methods to understand the properties of solutions of the PDEs under investigation.The proposed research involves two themes. The first is about a level-set mean curvature equation with driving and source terms, and applications to a crystal growth model, in which each level set of the unknown evolves in time by its mean curvature with unit constant force. The second involves Eikonal equations, and homogenization, where the zero-level set of the unknown moves in a periodic environment with highly oscillatory normal velocity.






To date, the PI hasbeen able to obtain some new and definitive research results in


(1) optimal rate of convegence in homogenization ofHamilton-Jacobi equations and shape of the effective fronts;


(2) level-set forced mean curvature flows and asymptotic growth speeds;


(3)a critical Coagulation-Fragmentation equation;


(4)optimal rates of convergence in homogenization of linear elliptic equations in non-divergence form;


(5) other topics on Hamilton-Jacobi equations:state constraints with applications to large deviations in games, numerical methods via Carleman estimates, regularity of degenerate problems.





Besides, the PI published a book title ``Hamilton--Jacobi equations: theory and applications, AMS Graduate Studies in Mathematics (Volume 213) in 2021. The book is self-contained and is useful for a course or for references. It can also serve as a gentle introductory reference to the homogenization theory.





The PI has organized various seminars, conferences, summer and winter schools for undergraduate and graduate students, and has given talks on the research findings both in the US and abroad. In particular, together with top experts in analysis and PDE from 8 other US universities, the PI has been co-organizing Virtual Analysis and PDE Seminar (VAPS) since Fall 2020 amid the pandemic. Also,Madison Workshop in PDE 2023 was a workshop for early career researchers in PDE supported by this grant.





During this period, four of the PI's graduate students got their PhDs and they were all benefited much from the support of this grant.


